                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/3970: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dennis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Corinto</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-10-25T10:00:00-05:45">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 25, 1926—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:56 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>178. Referring to Department’s number 95, October 20, 11 a.m.<note n="31"
                        xml:id="d504fn31">Not printed.</note> Admiral Latimer inquires whether use
                    of the term “belligerents” by the Department indicates recognition of
                    belligerency by the United States. I understand there is no recognition of
                    belligerency but admission of insurgency by the United States Government in
                    respect of contending factions on Atlantic coast of Nicaragua. Please instruct.
                    Repeated to Admiral.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dennis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
